{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:49:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:49:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14721"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14721"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.18,0.21,0.14,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58182"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7414"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43641"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3361"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18103"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58182"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is reviewing viral hepatitis during their microbiology rotation. They are particularly interested in the relationship between hepatitis B virus and hepatitis D virus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between hepatitis B virus and hepatitis D virus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis D virus suppresses hepatitis B viral replication","Hepatitis D virus integrates into the hepatitis B genome","Hepatitis B virus provides reverse transcriptase for hepatitis D replication","Hepatitis D virus uses the hepatitis B core antigen for assembly","Hepatitis B virus provides RNA-dependent RNA polymerase for hepatitis D"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis D virus (HDV) is a unique pathogen often described as a \u0027satellite virus\u0027. It requires helper functions from hepatitis B virus (HBV) to complete its life cycle. The key relationship is that HDV uses the hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) as its viral envelope, without which it cannot form complete viral particles or infect new cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis D virus suppresses hepatitis B viral replication\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Through mechanisms that are not fully elucidated, the presence of HDV typically results in reduced HBV replication. This suppression may occur through competition for cellular factors or direct interference with HBV replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis D virus integrates into the hepatitis B genome\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. HDV is an RNA virus and replicates in the nucleus using the host\u0027s RNA polymerase II. It does not integrate into the HBV genome or host genome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B virus provides reverse transcriptase for hepatitis D replication\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. HDV does not require reverse transcriptase for replication. It uses a rolling circle mechanism of replication similar to plant viroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis D virus uses the hepatitis B core antigen for assembly\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. HDV only requires the HBV surface antigen (HBsAg) for its envelope. The core antigen is not involved in HDV assembly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B virus provides RNA-dependent RNA polymerase for hepatitis D\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. HDV uses the host cell\u0027s RNA polymerase II for replication, not any viral polymerases from HBV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDV has the smallest genome of any known animal virus, encoding only one protein (the delta antigen). Despite its simplicity, it has evolved clever strategies to hijack both host cell machinery and HBV envelope proteins for its propagation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatitis D virus requires hepatitis B surface antigen to complete its life cycle and cannot replicate independently.","Hepatitis D virus is a defective RNA virus that uses hepatitis B surface antigen as its viral envelope.","The hepatitis D genome only codes for one protein (the delta antigen) and relies on host cell machinery for replication."],"references":["Asselah T, Rizzetto M. Hepatitis D Virus Infection [published correction appears in N Engl J Med. 2023 Oct 12;389(15):1444. doi: 10.1056/NEJMx230006]. N Engl J Med. 2023;389(1):58-70. doi:10.1056/NEJMra2212151","Negro F, Lok AS. Hepatitis D: A Review. JAMA. 2023;330(24):2376-2387. doi:10.1001/jama.2023.23242"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43641"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14721"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43641"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T20:30:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T20:31:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7414"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58182"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nu